    <p>Pow-wows are celebrations of Indigenous dances, music, foods, and crafts.
      They merge ceremonial and social elements, and represent a time and space to foster cultural pride, to enrich traditional heritage, and to celebrate resilience and healing.
      It's also an opportunity for cross-cultural sharing, including all Nations (Indigenous and non-Indigenous) and generations.
       In Canada, the 1876 Indian Act obstructed the celebration of powwows by restricting Indigenous peoples’
       right to conduct cultural and spiritual ceremonies and wear traditional outfits. Read more about the history of pow-wow <u><a href="https://www.encyclopediecanadienne.ca/en/article/history-of-powwows" target="_blank">here</u></a>. </p>
